**Abstract:**
A foundational project outline dated May 1, 1991, titled "Project-Chantilly," listing the underlying lines of the author's research project. The document identifies ten key themes including faith and reason, dramatic exposure, statement and narrative, the medievals' objections to Aristotelianism, speculative and practical reason, Nussbaum on akrasia, Sartre on being seen, being part of a history, and the narrative character of the Bible. It develops the concept of an "epistemological rupture" in the 12th-13th centuries when the Bible shifted from being read as the reader's history to becoming an object of scientific inquiry, with consequences for both faith and the humanities.

**AI Recommendation:** Essential programmatic document outlining the entire Chantilly project; provides the intellectual roadmap for understanding the other essays.

